Russia and Turkey: Alliance of the Marginalized?
A gesture that ended the crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce the end of an eight-month-long war of words and economic sanctions.
But Vladimir Putin's greeting of the Turkish leader in St. Petersburg's palace gave the impression that this partnership was more necessary for Ankara.
However, the two shook hands.
Vladimir Putin's smile looked artificial and did not cause warm emotions, even taking into account his usual restraint.
In contrast, Reed Tayyip Erdogan at least five times called Putin his "dear friend," according to a review of the meeting.
I was upset by the number.
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only improve to pre-crisis levels, but would become even stronger.
The next day, a newspaper reported that Erdogan had behaved as if nothing had happened.
In my opinion, his enthusiasm arouses conflicting feelings.
But the radiant coolness from Putin suggests that the Russian leader has not forgotten anything.
The first thing he mentioned in his address was the downing of a Russian plane on the Syrian border.
It was then that Moscow reacted sharply.
Putin accused Ankara of stabbing a dagger in Moscow's back.
The abuse was even more painful, given that it came from a friend's side.
Restoring true confidence will be very difficult, if not impossible.
Since November, however, Russia's public position has changed.
For several months, government-controlled television spread aggressive insults against Ankara.
Suddenly it seemed that the Turks were to blame for everything.
The most serious were the accusations that Erdogan's own family profited from the illegal oil trade with the Islamic State-controlled part of Syria.
He himself, of course, denied this.
But the main message of the St. Petersburg meeting is that it's time to forget the past.
After all, this meeting took place only because Putin received an apology from President Erdogan.
Russia might see this as a kind of victory.
Ankara's benefit from peace reconciliation is obvious.
First, Erdogan needs all possible friends after the failed coup last month in which he was attempted to overthrow.
The countless terrorist attacks have also shaken his position.
There are also economic motives.
Russian sanctions have caused severe damage, especially the ban on charter flights, which usually provide an influx of several million Russian tourists to Turkish resorts every year.
The number of tourists decreased by almost 90%.
Russian tour operators and charter companies will also breathe a sigh of relief when scheduled flights are restored.
They are hoping for a vacation fever in the Mediterranean at the end of the season.
Already this week, state TV is predicting a fall in fruit and vegetable prices due to the resumption of Turkish fruit and vegetable imports.
As the local newspaper Vedemosti quotes: "Tourists to them, tomatoes to us."
But the visit also had other political motives from the Moscow side.
Ankara is angry with the West for what they consider to be a weak response to the coup attempt.
Dissatisfaction with the protracted negotiations on EU accession and the intervention of Putin, who is happy to take advantage of the situation that Turkey has become estranged from the West, can also be seen in everything.
The Russian leader undoubtedly scored extra points in Ankara's eyes, expressing support for its elected government after the coup attempt.
Note that Moscow understands this well, because it itself has a deep-rooted fear of regime change in the country.
The summit, which took place in this luxurious seaside palace, gave Russia and Turkey the opportunity to present, as one analyst called it, an "outcast alliance", two countries that feel excluded from the West are joining forces.
But despite the unity publicly demonstrated, there are still significant differences of opinion between the two countries.
The main disagreements concern Syria, where Russia presents itself as a peacemaker, but in fact Russia and Turkey support the opposite sides.
After more than three hours of initial talks, unwilling to divulge information, the two presidents announced at a press conference that they had not discussed the issue.
The Turkish president purposefully avoided questions about the differences between the two countries, while President Putin wanted to emphasize them.
There is no clear consensus on how the two countries could find common ground on the Syrian issue.
But after months of openly hostile relations and a potential catastrophe when NATO member Turkey shot down a Russian fighter jet, the situation has improved as the two leaders have at least resumed talks.
The Royal Bank of Scotland will no longer be available to customers outside Scotland
