The drug by 2 pounds a day can reduce the risk of a heart attack.
Thousands of patients who have had a heart attack could be treated with the drug for 2 pounds a day, as official representatives recommend taking it to more people and for a longer period of time.
The anti-clotting medicine Ticagrelor reduces the risk of recurrent heart attacks in people with heart disease.
This drug is already prescribed for use 12 months after a heart attack, reducing the risk of a recurrent heart attack.
NICE, represented by the NHS, recommends taking this product 4 years after a heart attack to further reduce the risk of heart attack in people with cardiovascular problems.
However, NINE, currently under the responsibility of the NHS, recommends the use of this product 4 years after a heart attack to further reduce cardiovascular risk.
Every year, around 140,000 people in England experience a heart attack and a quarter of them experience a repeat heart attack or stroke.
A heart attack and stroke are caused by the accumulation of fatty substances in the walls of the heart, forming blockages.
If the blockage ruptures, it can produce a thrombus, blocking the flow of blood to the heart and causing a heart attack.
In turn, if the clot detaches from the wall of blood vessels, it can get further into the bloodstream and block the access of blood to the brain, causing a heart attack.
People who have had a heart attack are at a higher risk of recurrent heart attacks.
Ticagrelor, manufactured by the British firm AstraZeneca and marketed under the name Brilique, reduces the risk of blood clots.
The new NICE guidelines, published today, recommend that people take 90 mg of Ticagrelor for 12 months and another 3 years of 60 mg twice a day with aspirin.
Professor Carol Longson, director of health technology at NICE, explains: "Despite the availability of medications to prevent recurrent heart attacks, more than a quarter of people who have had a heart attack experience another heart attack or stroke, which often has severe consequences."
Fear of a repeated heart attack can have a negative impact on a person's quality of life.
Evidence suggests that Ticagrelor, combined with aspirin, effectively reduces the risk of recurrent heart attacks and heart attacks in people who have already experienced it.
By provisionally recommending treatment with Ticagrelor, we are pleased to be able to expand the treatment options for thousands of people, which is thus the winner.
In view of the limited information on the efficacy and safety of Ticagrelor, in particular the risk of bleeding when using this medicine for more than three years, the draft guidelines do not recommend that it be used beyond this period.
