The Islamic State has captured 2000 civilians in Syria.
Militants from the terrorist group Islamic State have taken captive about 2000 civilians used as human shields while fleeing Menbij, Syria's Aleppo province, the U.S.-backed Kurdish-Arab alliance and observers said Friday.
"We did not shoot at them because they took civilians with them while fleeing to Jerabulus," a spokesman for the Kurdish Menbij Military Council said.
After two months of fighting, the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (QSD), a U.S.-backed Kurdish-Arab alliance in northern Syria, announced Friday that Menbij had been liberated from the jihadists.
The Islamic State occupied Menbij in 2014.
The QSD had already driven most Islamic State militants out of Menbij last week, but some held on and showed fierce resistance.
However, on Friday they left the city, taking their captives with them.
Islamists go to Jerabulus, which is located on the Turkish border.
The London-based Syrian activist organization Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (SOHR) also reported that the Islamic State kidnapped about 2000 people.
SOHR reported that Islamists hijacked the cars of city dwellers, forced people to get into them, and then took them to Jerabulus.
Islamic State militants have also carried out mass kidnappings in the past.
In January, Islamists kidnapped more than 400 civilians, including women and children, while conquering territories in Deir ez Zora province in eastern Syria.
Later, about 270 of the captives were released by the Islamists.
How many Islamic State militants fled Menbij is unknown.
A spokesman for the Kurdish Menbij Military Council reported that the QSD had managed to rescue 2500 people held captive by Islamists in Menbij.
Information gathered by SOHR shows that at least 437 civilians, including 105 children, lost their lives in the battle for Menbij.
299 QSD fighters and 1019 jihadists were killed.
