German researchers are debating the number of "victims of the Berlin Wall".
According to a new study, the death toll at the communist yoke on the former East German border could be much higher than previously thought, but doubts about the true number of victims remain unsettled.
According to data released on Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989, 1841 people who tried to escape from the territory under their control were murdered by communist authorities on the border with western Allied zones and later West Germany.
The museum has been studying border-related deaths for years and adjusts the number of victims from time to time.
This year, 11 more deaths have been added to the list, including a six-year-old boy who drowned as his family tried to get to West Germany through what was then Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall are also deserters of the Soviet army.
"The final extent of the damage caused by the double evils of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented," says Alexandra Hildebrandt, the museum's director.
"Our job is to ensure that the graves of those who died trying to escape from the communist-controlled country are maintained and do not disappear," a statement released by Hildebrandt said.
But other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
"The figure of 1841 is inconclusive," says Johen Stath, an expert in East German history at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung.
He, along with other researchers at the Free University of Berlin, is currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have managed to confirm only 260 cases.
Previously, researchers estimated that just off the Berlin Wall, 138 people were murdered by communists.
Taking into account those people who died trying to escape through the Baltic Sea or get to the West through the territory of neighboring countries, according to Stadt, the number of victims could reach about a thousand.
But that's significantly less than 1841 anyway.
One of the reasons for the different number of victims could be the different methodologies.
The Checkpoint Charlie Museum also lists all cases of suicide by East German border guards, regardless of whether they were directly related to their service.
The museum also lists deaths that are not related to direct violence.
"If seniors between the ages of 70 and 80 died of a heart attack after shrinking with border controls," that must be a consequence of this 'murderous boundary', according to Hildebrandt.
But Stath is convinced that a distinction needs to be made between the elderly, who may have died as a result of the treatment they experienced, and those whose deaths were caused by prolonged waits in hot weather on a bus at the border.
Regardless, accounting for victims is not easy, as communist East German authorities did not accumulate such statistics, and researchers have to dig through documents in various scattered archives, according to Stath.
However, Stath's group has recently come across new documents, and so it could come up with a new estimate of the number of victims in the near future.
