600,000 juvenile salmon will be released into the Daugava River.
During the Latvenergo AS fish resource recovery programme, salmon and sea trout juveniles are being released this week in the Daugava river near Mangaļsala, and this year it is planned to release more than 600,000 juvenile annual salmon and sea trout grown in the fish farms of the scientific institute Bior Tomes and Dole.
Latvenergo agency LETA informed that the introduction of fish will continue for the coming months - every year a total of 6,300,000 juveniles and larvae of various species of fish are allowed into the water bodies of the Daugava basin.
In the spring and beginning of summer 2016, pike and lamprey larvae will be released, in June - whitefish, in July - one-summer salmon, in August and September - zanders and vimbas.
Māris Kuņickis, Latvenergo's production director, said that taking care of the environment is one of the cornerstones of Latvenergo Group's sustainable development.
"In the measures for the protection and reproduction of fish resources, each activity is aimed at environmentally friendly actions in close cooperation with the scientific institute Bior, carrying out both the rearing and release of juvenile fish into the Daugava basin, as well as implementing other activities," said Kuņickis.
This year, more than 600,000 juvenile annual salmon and sea trout will be allowed into the Daugava estuary.
For the second year, fish fry are marked before being let in by cutting off the buttercup.
The cargo brought today contains 25,000 juvenile salmon with an average weight of 31.3 grams.
Every year, in a scientifically based species composition and numerical volume, juvenile fish and larvae are introduced into the Daugava river and its basin water bodies.
Reproduction of fish resources in the Daugava River and the water bodies of its basin in accordance with laws and regulations shall be performed by the Bior on the basis of an expert-examination of the losses caused to fish resources as a result of Latvenergo's economic activity and providing a conclusion on what compensatory measures should be taken in order to ensure the diversity of fish resources.
In turn, the State Environmental Service, on the basis of the abovementioned expert-examination, shall take a decision on the amount and type of compensation.
Latvenergo's annual compensation amount for the fish resource recovery programme is EUR 1 035 000.
In the spring of 2016, Latvenergo, in cooperation with the association "We fish", for the fifth year placed 400 artificial fish spawning nests in the Daugava river near Kaibala and Ikšķile.
Cooperation with the association in promoting natural spawning of fish is an additionally supported initiative of Latvenergo within the framework of the fish resource recovery program.
The placement of artificial spawning nests in the watershed is an important measure that contributes to the protection and reproduction of fish resources in the Daugava River.
