A French court rejects the request to demolish shops in the "Jungle" refugee camp.
A French court rejected a request by the Calais authorities to demolish dozens of self-made shops and restaurants in the "Jungle" camp, where several thousand refugees live.
At a hearing in Calais this week, authorities said the state should demolish 72 self-made boutiques where people in the camp area sell a variety of goods such as cigarettes and energy drinks, offer hairdressing, tea for 50 cents (40p) and simple meals for a few euros in self-made restaurants.
Calais's prefect's office said these self-created businesses need to be demolished because they form a shadow economy and do not pay taxes, as well as pose fire and sanitary risks.
Representatives of the humanitarian group explained to the court that these small businesses are essential because the food provided by the government and support groups does not meet the needs of the camp, where the number of residents continues to grow.
They also pointed out that self-made boutiques and restaurants often offer free shelter and food to those who need it most.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to expel the people who set up the 72 self-made boutiques, but it understands Calais's prefect's concerns.
Judge Jean-François Molla said food, coffee and restaurants play a bigger role than simply providing food to people living in "extremely sublime conditions."
He pointed out that these places are peaceful meeting places for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places at risk of demolition is the jungle book kids camp café, which provides more than 200 free meals a day, English and French classes, and provides asylum counselling to hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect a children's café.
A letter to the Guardian stated that the dissolution of the café "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are only 8 years old."
On Friday, two charities, Aid for Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants, reported that the number of residents of the "Jungle" camp had risen to 9000 people, the highest rate since the rapid influx of migrants in the summer.
Great Britain wins silver in the rugby-7 series fight when the Fiji national team masterfully wins gold.
The British national team's impressive performance in the rugby-7 series stage ended on Thursday when, in a thrilling final at the Deodoro Stadium in Rio, the Fiji national team convincingly crushed them by a score of 43-7.
Fiji demonstrated a master class in ball management, ball play with the foot, support game and brute power play, winning gold - the first Olympic medal in its history.
The defeat brought a respectable consolation award, a silver medal that was Britain's third medal that day. The British national team can be proud of their success in the first Olympic rugby-7 tournament, in which they defeated New Zealand, Argentina and South Africa.
The tough fight in the semi-finals, in which the Bok team suffered a defeat with a score of 7:5 in the first half of the day, probably rebounded for Great Britain in the final.
But in any case, the Fiji national team is currently in its best shape to win the 15-man team as well.
Although unlikely, however, a certain consolation for Britain could be the fact that at least one Briton won a gold medal. This is the head coach of the Fiji national team Ben Ryan - a former England coach from Wimbledon.
It was an exciting adventure for Britain.
Eight years ago, under Ryan's leadership, they lost all their games in the rugby-7 series stage in Adelaide.
This time they lost only one game.
The defeat is painful, but the growth is amazing.
Fiji made an impressive start to the match, fending off Britain's power plays for fun.
For captain Tom Mitchell and comrades, it was like racing with several opposing buses and the World Series champions took the lead with 5-0 when Osea Kolinisau scored his first touchdown.
In the final four minutes, Jerry Tuwai also further increased the lead by realizing a groundout on the right wing.
The score was 12-0 and the British team hadn't even really touched the ball.
Mitchell's superb power play prevented the humble Leoni Nakarav from scoring three points, but that only slightly affected Fiji's score.
In the seventh minute of the game, Jasa Veremalua scored a grounder in the right corner, cementing the lead over Great Britain to 17-0.
After the rematch, Nakarava further increased the lead and had more than a minute left until the end... the end of the first half.
Vatemo Ravouvou avoided some clumsy British power techniques and crossed the line, scoring points.
The groundout secured the score at 29-0.
Fiji seemed to have been born to play rugby-7 matches while the British were still learning.
In fact, that is also true.
The British team made a profound change at halftime, breaking the Fiji players' line... a full four minutes, which was good by the standards of the first half, until Joshua Tuisova, after a fantastic team matchup, scored a few more points for the Fiji team.
Dan Norton managed to score for the British team, making a landing in the left corner and making the score 36-7, but the game was already lost, meanwhile fans of the South Sea Islanders were singing, waving flags and dancing in the stands.
One cannot help but admire Fiji's cheerful attitude.
Mata Viliame made Fiji's victory even sweeter with another touchdown at the end of the game.
With the final whistle of the game sounding, Fiji could start celebrating, but the British were able to sit down in the grass after the defeat.
In the first half of the day, in the semifinals, Fiji defeated Japan by a score of 20:5, while the British were superior to South Africa, where in a very fierce battle both teams scored a touchdown and the South Africans lost by only a few points.
In the first half, Kyle Brown put the Bok team in the lead, but in the second half, Dan Norton crossed the line with brilliant skill and delivered the ball between the posts, securing the victory for the British.
The excellent power play of Marcus Watson, who is the brother of England rugby-15 team player Anthony, at the end of the game ensured the team a win and another silver medal.
