In Spain, the prospects for reducing the budget deficit are threatened by the inability to form a government.
On 12 July a month ago, the European Commission (EC) issued an opinion that Spain and Portugal had not taken measures of sufficient magnitude to bring the deficit level down to the 3% of gross domestic product (GDP) required by the euro area.
It is estimated that, despite the austerity measures implemented, Portugal's budget deficit at the end of last year was 4.4% of GDP and Spain's deficit was 5.1%.
The European Commission, however, decided not to impose economic sanctions on both countries, while at the same time setting fiscal targets for the near term.
One of the reasons why the EC did not, however, introduce sanctions against these two countries is the growing Euroscepticism in many countries of the European Union.
Additional sanctions would only add to such a negative sentiment.
Critics, however, point out that the EC is not consistent in its decisions, first agreeing on uniform rules and then failing to apply them in practice.
Thus, for example, the President of the German Bundesbank, Jens Weidmann, has pointed out that Europe is losing confidence in itself in this way, giving citizens the impression that the rules of the European Union are recommendatory rather than binding.
The EC has now proposed and all Member States have approved to extend the deadline for correcting their deficits until the end of this year for Portugal and until 2018 for Spain.
The European Commission promises to examine the progress made by both countries in the coming months, while pointing out that both Spain and Portugal must be prepared to introduce additional austerity measures if circumstances so require.
Initial forecasts suggest that Portugal's target could be achieved on time, and that the deficit could fall to 2.5% of gross domestic product as early as this year.
This means that, as part of the Stability Programme, the government of this country must implement austerity measures of 0.25% of GDP this year.
These measures should be included in this year's budget, with an additional focus on controlling the cost of purchasing goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complicated.
This year, the budget deficit should be reduced to 4.6%, next year - to 3.1% and in 2018 - to 2.2% of GDP.
In addition, consolidation measures should be 0.5% of GDP annually over the next two years.
What makes it particularly difficult to achieve these objectives is the fact that for eight months now the Spanish political parties have failed to agree on the formation of a government, and it is becoming increasingly likely that Spain may have to hold early parliamentary elections for the third time in a year.
However, opinion polls show that a third election would not significantly change the political landscape in the country either.
The most popular party remains the people's party led by current Prime Minister Mariano Rahoja, which would again win less than 33% of the vote in the election.
Only the Socialists have slightly increased their popularity, while the anti-austerity parties Podemos, or Together We Can, and Ciudadanos, or Citizens, have declined somewhat.
The People's Party wants to get the Socialists and Ciudadanos involved in government later this month, otherwise it will not be able to adopt and submit the draft budget for 2017 to the European Commission for approval by mid-October.
As Rafael Hernando, a spokesman for the People's Party's parliamentary faction, has stated, if the government is not formed and parliamentary elections are held for the third time, Spain will become a mockery of the whole of Europe.
The cleanliness of the beaches in the Gulf of Riga is critical.
After surveying the beaches for the fifth year, activists have concluded that, unfortunately, the number of garbage found is increasing every year, and most of the visitors to the bathing areas are to blame here.
The most polluted bathing areas are in Riga.
The capital city council explains that bathing areas are cleaned up every day, but it is quite difficult to fight against dirty visitors.
In addition, waste left on land during heavy rains can be washed into the water, thus significantly damaging its quality.
With the exception of Liepaja beach and some places in Kurzeme, the cleanliness of beaches elsewhere in Latvia is critical.
Such a statement was made this week by volunteers of the "My Sea" campaign.
After walking along the Gulf of Riga for the fifth year, activists have concluded that the number of waste left by residents has increased every hundred meters.
Unfortunately, this year, that criticality rating has set in.
"We see that this will be the year when the number of garbage on the beach for 100 meters may even exceed 200 units", says Jānis Ulme, a representative of the expedition "My Sea".
Called by Latvian Radio, he was on the beach of Tūja, where the procession of volunteers along the Gulf of Riga continues.
This year, among the various household waste and remnants of picnics, activists have had to collect even fluorescent lamps left tossed in the sea sand.
Ulme, a participant and organizer of the hike, says it is the residents who are to blame for the pollution.
"The main source is the beachgoers themselves, because more than half of the total amount of waste is plastic, various waste, starting with bags, pieces of plastic that are already in the stage of degradation, it is no longer possible to identify them, and mock-ups, bottles, corks," says Ulme.
Among the dirtiest beaches there are also swimming areas in Riga.
For example, in Daugavgrīva, on average, almost 800 units of waste are collected every hundred meters, which is a critical amount.
Campaign organisers also explain that there are also mock-ups and warning or prohibition signs not everywhere at every turn.
"Unfortunately, the average figures for all three bathing sites in Riga together - Daugavgriva, Vakarbuļļi and Vecaķi - are large and far exceed the desired or the goal to which Latvia is supposedly moving to reduce the number of waste units to 135 units by 2020", concludes the environmental defender.
Cleaning of bathing areas in Riga takes place every day, on the hottest days of summer even twice, explains the representative of the city council Uģis Vidauskis.
However, the struggle with dirty visitors is quite difficult.
We come back to the cultural issue of these people.
"Those who eat alcohol, smoke and do all the things they can't, even special signs don't work," Vidauski says.
That's why Vidauski is urging bathing visitors to report pollutants to the police as well.
You can call the police, safely point out these violations and in this way everyone will fight.
Perhaps some new warnings can be imposed, but as I said, this is unlikely to radically change the situation.
"Because everyone together just has to turn around and be intolerant of such offenders," he stresses.
Meanwhile, water quality measurements have been carried out for the fourth time this summer by the Health Inspectorate, which may impose a ban on official bathing sites.
This year, however, as in other years, the water quality everywhere is good and satisfactory.
At the moment, the situation is such that in all 56 bathing areas the water quality has been good all the time and there are no restrictions on bathing.
"One last time we will take the tests at the end of August," says Normunds Juniķis, senior environmental health specialist at the inspectorate.
During heavy rainfall, waste left on land can be washed into the water.
This, in turn, can affect its quality, according to an environmentalist.
Rotations in the Russian elite continue - in the Putin administration, the change of leader.
Left office himself?
Vladimir Putin has told Russian media that Sergei Ivanov wanted to leave the post himself and will henceforth be the president's special representative on nature conservation, ecology and transport.
Announcing the changes, Putin paid tribute to Ivanov in front of the television cameras: "Dear Sergey Borisovich, we have been working together with you for many years and are doing it successfully."
I am satisfied with the way in which you are fulfilling the duties entrusted to you.
I remember well of our agreement not to use you in this position as head of the presidential administration for more than four years.
