However, it is highlighted that the leadership of the presidential administration is a very important position and this made Ivanov one of the most influential people in the country.
Considering that elections to the State Duma are expected in Russia next month, rumors have sounded that this move is connected with the struggle for power among the Russian political elite.
Ivanov was also called a possible replacement for Putin as president, so the claim that he himself wanted to take the post of presidential representative on nature conservation and transport issues has raised doubts.
As the archives of Lsm.lv show, Ivanov is a general colonel of the KGB and the Federal Security Service.
Ivanov has been an old and close ally of Russian President Vladimir Putin.
He began his career in the special services in 1975, where he met Putin.
Later, when Putin became the head of the Federal Security Service, Ivanov became his deputy.
In turn, at the end of the reign of the first Russian president Boris Yeltsin, he was appointed secretary of the Russian Security Council.
In 2000, after Putin came to power, the "Doctrine of Information Security" developed by Ivanov was approved, which, among other things, in Russia provided for the revival of state censorship mechanisms.
In 2001, Sergey Ivanov became the Minister of Defense of Russia, and already in 2005 - deputy prime minister Mikhail Fradkov and was responsible for the development of enterprises in the Russian defense industry and the export of weapons.
Now, after leaving the post of head of the presidential administration, Ivanov will also retain his seat on the Russian National Security Council, where the new head of the presidential administration, Vaino, will now also work.
The blame comes from a family in the elite of the Soviet party.
The post of head of the presidential administration, Vaino, was allegedly recommended by Ivanov himself.
Anton Eduardovich and I have known each other for a long time.
Back in the days when we worked in government under your leadership.
And for the past nearly five years, we've been communicating virtually every day.
"Therefore, I am sure that by all professional and personal character traits, he is ready for this job", said Ivanov.
The blame comes from a family that belonged to the elite of the Soviet party.
His grandfather Karl held high positions in the Estonian Communist Party, including serving as its first secretary for ten years until 1988.
The Internet publication "Meduza", with a reference to the book "Estonian self-determination and independence", writes that in the late 80s Karl Vaino allegedly asked Moscow for permission to use force against demonstrators.
However, he was refused and soon lost his post.
Shortly after, Vaino has moved to live in Moscow.
Anton Vaino graduated from the Moscow Institute of International Relations and is fluent in Japanese.
However, he has retired from the diplomatic service to work for the Presidential Protocol Administration.
