Before the 40th anniversary of "Līvu", the legendary rock band can be explored at the exhibition in Liepaja.
The exhibition will feature various objects characterizing "Līvus" - photographs, which are arranged in a time line to reflect the group's activities from the beginning until 2010, when the end of the group's activities is announced.
The participants' stage costumes, musical instruments, awards and concert recordings, as well as other things not yet seen by the general public, which reflected the creative activity of the group "Līvi", will also be shown.
The exhibition will be supplemented with objects from the Liepaja Museum collection.
The visual design of the exhibition was created in cooperation with fashion artist and painter Elita Patmalniece.
Musicians who have been associated with the band "Livy" and their relatives also responded to the call and shared both objects and memories.
The origins of "Līvu" can be traced back to 1972, when a vocal-instrumental ensemble was created in the Liepaja House of Culture, which was led by Juris Pavītols.
The ensemble participated in the festival "Liepajas dzintars" in 1972 and 1974, as well as in city and republic shows.
In 1976, a fateful meeting took place, when Juris Pavītols met Ēriks Ķiģelis and founded a group in the Metallurgical Palace of Culture, inviting Ingrida Gutmanis, Andris Kriņš and Jānis Grodums to join.
Over the years, the composition of the group has changed more than once.
Participants have joined, others have gone their own way, some have returned.
However, most importantly, the desire to confirm that Latvian rock music is capable of living and existing - has remained the same.
"There was no shortage of things to see - jeans, hairy and bearded, these boys were noticeably different from the generally accepted stereotype of stage singing," music reviewer Klaas Squirrel says of the band.
In addition to the aforementioned musicians, the group has included such outstanding musicians as Hugo, Vilnis Krieviņš, Modris Šterns, Valdis Štarks, Fortunates Rācenājs, Tālis Pusbarnieks, Ainars Virga, Aivars Brīze, Guntars Mucenieks, Dainis Virga, Tomass Kleins and many others.
Admission to the exhibition is free of charge.
The exhibition is on view from August 19 to October 30.
On August 27, liepaja concert garden "Blew, winds" will host the 40th anniversary celebration of the group "Līvi" "LĪVIfest 2".
For the first time in 8 months, Bulgaria is experiencing inflation.
In July, Bulgarian national statistics showed a monthly inflation rate of 1%.
That's the highest rate since 2012 and the first above zero since October of the previous year, when it was positive at 0.2%.
The average annual inflation by CPI in the last 12 months (August 2015 - July 2016) compared to the previous year was -0.8%.
The consumer price index in July 2016, compared to the previous year, was 101.9% and the average monthly inflation was 1.0%.
Since the beginning of the year, the inflation rate was -0.2% (in July 2016 compared to December 2015) and annual inflation in July 2016 compared to July 2015 was -0.2%.
Compared to the previous month, in July 2016 there was an increase in prices for the following groups of consumer goods: food and non-alcoholic beverages (1.7%); transport (1.8%); entertainment and cultural events (6.3%); hotels and restaurants (1.2%); household goods and services (0.3%).
Decline was registered in prices of clothing and footwear (2.2%); housing equipment, household appliances and regular house cleaning (0.5%); health (0.1%).
Prices remained at the level of the previous month for alcohol and tobacco, management, water, electricity, gas and other fuels, communications and education.
