The reconstructed section of the road has been discovered in Medumos.
Minister of Transport Uldis Augulis, SJSC Latvian State Roads (LVC) management, as well as representatives of builders SIA "Binders" and local governments today opened the reconstructed section of the main state highway Russian border (Grebneva) -Rēzekne-Daugavpils-Lithuanian border (Medumi) (A13) from Medumi to the Lithuanian border (km 156.4-163.05).
Roads are the calling card of the country, especially border roads, so it is especially gratifying to discover a reconstructed section on the border with our southern neighbors.
This is another example of the fact that, thanks to the cofinancing of European Union funds, the situation on the country's main roads is improving.
"According to the forecasts, during this planning period the funds available for roads will be absorbed already in 2018, and we need to think about how to continue to maintain the most congested motorways in very good quality, and also to ensure the mobility of residents in all regions of Latvia without funding from the European Union", Uldis Augulis emphasized by cutting the symbolic ribbon.
The Minister of Transport also indicated that the proposals prepared by traffic experts on sustainable financing of Latvian roads in the near future will be presented to the government.
Binders Ltd. started construction works on the section from Medumi to the Lithuanian border (km 156.4-163.05) last year and this year they continued after a technological break.
The reconstruction costs are 13.5 million euros (including VAT), the project was co-financed by the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF).
"In the reconstructed section of the road, the road structure has been completely restored and next year repair works will be started on the next stage from Medumi to Daugavpils itself, thus the entire road from the Lithuanian border to Daugavpils will be arranged," informed Jānis Lange, Chairman of the Board of LVC.
The main highways of the country are the most congested, and by 2018 we plan to ensure that all the main highways of the country are in good condition.
The next task will be to maintain them in good quality, timely ensuring periodic maintenance and carrying out the replacement of the asphalt topcoat every 7-9 years.
"This will, of course, require adequate funding, and all roadrunners are looking forward to the proposals made by the expert group to clean up the road financing system," Lange noted.
Within the framework of the project, road connections and lighting in the Medumu center have been arranged.
Significant earthworks have been carried out: in four stages, large-scale dewatering and extensive excavation and embankment work, leveled the longitudinal profile of the road, which until now was very uneven.
Public transport stops have also been renovated and a turning area for public transport has been rebuilt.
Previously, the road had insufficient bearing capacity and the terrain of the terrain was not transparent due to the mountainous valleys, as well as the old road copied the terrain.
In the next construction season, it is planned to restore the section of the motorway from Daugavpils city border to the now reconstructed section (km 144.80-156.40).
This year, LVC plans to carry out various types of work on more than 1100 kilometers of state roads.
Information on all the repairs planned in the State motorway network this year is available on the LVC website www.lvceli.lv.
"To achieve the desired results of weight loss, the right choice of food combinations is very important", admits Lithuanian nutritionist Laura Romeraite-Kuklieriene.
In addition, it is easy to do in the summer period, when fresh fruits, berries and vegetables grow in our own gardens.
Thoughtful combination of dietary products can help not only reduce excess weight, but also purposefully promote various processes in the body.
Pasta and vinegar are a successful combination, as they provide a long-lasting feeling of satiety and help fight fat.
Studies published in the European Journal of Clinical Nutrition have shown that vinegar has a beneficial effect on blood glucose levels and helps us feel lively.
Cayenne pepper and protein-rich foods such as poultry or protein cocktail not only create a feeling of satiety, but also reduce cravings for large meals at subsequent meals.
Such a combination of dishes is also able to increase the amount of calories burned after a meal by up to 35%.
Studies have shown that cayenne pepper can help get rid of the fat layer in the abdominal area.
The composition of eggs contains a metabolism-boosting nutrient - choline, while paprika is a good source of vitamin C.
Ingesting enough of these nutrients can reduce cortisol levels, hence the accumulation of fat around the middle of the body.
Oatmeal porridge, to which fresh berries are added, is another delicious and fat-burning meal for breakfast that is worth including in your menu.
Oatmeal and berries contain fiber, which, according to the conclusions of Canadian scientists, controls grelin - an appetite-stimulating hormone - and therefore a feeling of hunger.
In addition, the berries contain polyphenols, which are helpers in weight loss, and also do not allow the formation of fat.
Vegetables and proteins are also able to do wonders in weight loss.
Such a combination is able to create a feeling of satiety.
Vegetables contain water and fiber, so they contribute to the feeling of satiety.
At the same time, protein slows down the digestive process and provides a feeling of satiety for a longer period of time.
For lunch, you can eat chicken with a salad, or you can make a protein cocktail from the finished mixture and enjoy it with your favorite vegetables.
What combinations of products to avoid.
In the fruit there are sugars - monosaccharides or disaccharides - compounds of one or two molecules.
In contrast, starch, which is contained in vegetables, is a polysaccharide.
Fruits decompose in the stomach mechanically, while chemically they do not decompose until they reach the third or fourth degree in the process of digestion that occurs in the intestine.
Starch breaks down into three different stages, which begin already in the mouth.
Therefore, it is essential not to eat sweet food immediately after a meal.
When eating sweet food immediately after a meal, it is "trapped" in the stomach along with other dishes, where it is not chemically digested and begins to rot.
Do not eat bread, potatoes, peas, bananas, dates or other carbohydrate-containing products along with lemons, lime, oranges, grapefruit, pineapples or other acidic fruits.
The enzyme ptialin, which is contained in saliva, acts only in an alkaline environment.
Fruit acids inhibit not only the digestion of carbohydrates, but also contribute to their fermentation.
Do not eat eggs and meat, nuts and meat, cheese and eggs or cheese and nuts, meat and milk, eggs and milk or nuts and milk and similar combinations of protein-rich products in one meal.
Their processing requires different digestive juices, each with different strength, features and the time to enter the stomach.
Watermelon, honeymoon, muscatel and other melons should always be eaten separately from other dishes.
Melons are not digested if they are in the stomach along with other foods.
Fat in combination with protein-rich products.
Fat forms a successful combination with starch, however, the same cannot be said about fats and proteins - fats inhibit the digestion of proteins.
Proteins can be combined with a very small amount of fat.
If a large amount of protein-containing products is consumed, avoid consuming fat altogether.
This also applies to anointing - it is not recommended to combine a large amount of nuts (contains protein) with whole avocados (contains fat).
Such a combination inhibits effective weight reduction.
How better to cook?
"Cooking, heat treatment leads to a significant loss of nutrients - about 15% to 55% of the initial nutritional composition of the products", states the nutritionist.
In most cases, nutrients go to waste by boiling foods in water.
However, the nutritional value of certain foods increases with direct boiling.
The liquid remaining after boiling the vegetables is recommended to be used to make soup - in this case, you will not lose the nutrients left in the water and will be able to eat them later.
It is recommended to cook vegetables, also steaming them.
Heat treatment significantly increases the bioavailability of lycopene contained in tomatoes.
When boiling tomatoes for 30 minutes, the amount of lycopene increases by 25%.
Heat treatment also significantly increases the bioavailability of betacarotin, which is found in red, yellow, orange plants such as tomatoes, carrots, sweet potatoes and spinach.
Heat treatment of eggs and meat deprives them of the natural properties of the proteins contained in them, making them easier to digest.
Also, heat treatment of meat and eggs makes iron and other minerals in the composition of these products easier to absorb by the body.
It should also be borne in mind that freezing products can reduce the amount of vitamin C from 10% to as much as 90%, while freezing fiber does not affect.
Beans in combination with tomatoes can increase iron intake in the body, which in turn provides better brain and muscle function.
Our body absorbs up to 33% less non-blood-producing iron, which is found in plant products such as beans, leafy greens, cereal products, than blood-producing iron, which is found in animal products such as beef, fish and chicken.
You can significantly increase the absorption of non-hematopoietic iron by consuming non-hematopoietic iron-containing products along with sources of vitamin C, such as oranges, tomatoes and berries.
Vitamin C helps to change non-hematopoietic iron so that it is more easily absorbed by our body.
Iron is necessary for the production of hemoglobin, which ensures the delivery of oxygen to the muscles and brain.
To get the most out of salads, add healthy fats to them, such as olive or linseed oil.
When making sandwiches with salmon, add to the vitamin D-rich salmon or sardines a non-additive yogurt, which is a good source of calcium.
Vitamin D increases the amount of calcium absorbed in the intestine and plays a vital role in the process of bone formation.
Oats (as well as other whole grain products), along with sources of vitamin C such as strawberries, black currants, raspberries and other fruits or berries, help stabilize cholesterol levels, as well as avoid blockage of the arteries.
Snapchat "Anime" effect criticized for caricaturing asians
Snapchat representatives say that this filter is inspired by the animation but some commentators claim that it is racially insensitive.
With this lens effect, Snapchat allows 150 million users to change reality and play with their identity in a rather absurd way on a daily basis.
You can turn yourself into a pineapple, a dog, or an image that would fit into a painting by Roy Lichstanstein.
Lenses are hazy, image-crippling tools that generate more than 30 million converted selfies a day.
Any mistake quickly becomes publicly noticeable.
Snapchat's lens effects have been criticized in the past, with accusations that the app promotes overly blackish or light facial skin tones as the benchmark for perfect beauty.
This week, the new lens effects were published that allow users to create crooked eyes, crooked teeth and round cheeks, and some critics dubbed it a racist Asian caricature – "yellow gimmick."
It was also questioned whether such contradictions suggest that the company has bigger problems with diversity.
News and public negations flared up on Wednesday when The Verge and Motherboard announced that lens effects had been removed from the app.
The company explained that the purpose of the lens is to depict Anime characters, not to caricature people of Asian descent.
But for people who have experienced racism, these effects resembled painful stereotypes.
Others categorically denied the similarity with Anime.
A Twitter post about the images by Korean-American art student Grace Sparapani gained widespread resonance. In an email, she states that the lens effects were "offensive and uncomfortable, to say the least."
She added that it's hard not to notice the apparent similarity between Asian cartoons and lens effects.
This suggests that the lens effect is not simply a yellow face, but a yellow face in the sense of racism.
Snapchat isn't the only company that has fallen into this cultural trap.
American culture is also engaged in an endless struggle for diversity and inclusion, from business meeting rooms to Hollywood and the devices we use on a daily basis.
And on Snapchat, the large audience of young people, representing different races, unlike the older population, is more sensitive to such things.
If Snapchat's lenses create an image that offends users, then "things like this don't go unnoticed these days," 25-year-old Katie Zhou said in an interview on Thursday.
On Thursday, Zhou, product manager at Medium, deleted his Snapchat app and advised others to do the same.
In her article on "Medium" and in a telephone interview, she explained that she believes the problems with race are due to Snapchat's employment policies, which do not sufficiently support racial diversity.
Zhou criticized the management of the company, which consists mainly of white men, and then concluded his article with a reference to #DeleteSnapchat.
"This means that there is no racial diversity in the company, so such decisions are made. Does the company employ some representatives of other races, but they do not hold such a position as to be able to safely and comfortably express their opinion", according to Zhou, an American of Chinese descent.
Her opinion is shared by others, while Snapchat has not responded to her complaint.
The company does not disclose how many employees are represented by different races, indicating that it is a private company.
Snapchat declined to discuss the origins of its employees, but its spokesperson revealed that the company has hired an HR specialist who will focus on also representing racial minorities in the company who are not widely represented and will promote inclusion in the company.
Zhou, on the other hand, won't be renewing his Snapchat account, adding, "I wonder if they really need more users like us to realize it's not right."
The House of Congress says military officials misrepresented reports of the Islamic State.
In a statement issued Thursday, the House of Congress said U.S. Central Command had distorted the reports, portraying the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria far more optimistically than it actually is.
Central Command intelligence analysts express general dissatisfaction with the interim report of the Republican task unit set up by the Republican representatives of the Armed Forces Committee, the Intelligence Committee and the Subcommittee on Defense Financing, noting that their leadership controlled reports of American success in the fight against the Islamic State.
Central Command, known as Centcom, is a military base in Tampa, Florida that oversees U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
The latest news of the report says intelligence reports confirmed by high-ranking Centcom executives reflect the U.S. fight against terrorism more positively than it actually is. The facts were regularly distorted, depicting better achievements than other intelligence analyses suggest.
California Republican spokesman Ken Calvert says, "Centcom's actions are unacceptable — our soldiers are the ones who suffer when our policymakers get false reports."
Centcom's management mistakes lie in the organization's top management.
This 10-page report details the challenges facing Central Command's coverage and analysis of American efforts to prepare Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While it does not provide conclusive evidence that senior officials in the Obama administration have led to misrepresentation of the reports, it does show that Centcom's leadership has put some pressure on analysts to portray a more optimistic view of the threat posed by the Islamic State (also known as ISIS or ISIL).
The report notes that in the first half of 2015, press releases, statements and reports from the Central Administration to Congress portrayed the situation in a significantly more positive light than it actually was.
For example, Centcom representatives publicly stated that the Mosul recovery operation could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul is Iraq's second-largest city, still under Islamic State control.
Kansas Republican Party spokesman Mike Pompeo says in his report, "Months of investigation clearly demonstrate this."
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, key officials in the U.S. Central Administration distorted the reports, portraying the ISIS threat in Iraq weaker than it actually was.
The Republican Party set up a task force to learn that analysts are concerned that information about the Islamic State is being distorted.
As the investigation continues, a report released Thursday will be followed by new findings in the case.
The General Inspectorate of the Ministry of Defense conducts an investigation into the activities of the Centcom intelligence service.
Members of the Intelligence Administration Committee's Democratic Party released their own report Thursday in which they agree with some of the findings of the Republican Party task force.
Democrat spokesman Adam B. Schiff says in his report, from 2014 to 2015, Centcom too restricted the preparation of intelligence assessment reports related to ISIS and the Iraqi Security Forces.
Mr. Schiff explains that the process "stopped the dissemination of information," worsened analysts' work ethic, and "spread untrue facts."
But Schiff and Democratic Party members added that there was no evidence that the White House had pressured Centcom analysts to draft reports in accordance with "predetermined or political positions."
The Daily Beast on Thursday published the preliminary results of the congressional investigation.
In August, The New York Times reported that the Pentagon's general inspectorate had launched an investigation following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Pentagon spokesman Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans said the Pentagon would not comment on the congressional report while the investigation continues.
He also added that experts sometimes interpret complex data in different ways, and the Ministry of Defense and the intelligence department call for a constructive dialogue on vital national security issues.
The investigation is not limited to the question of whether the American-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is successful (a claim made by an increasing number of representatives of the Ministry of Defense).
But last year's accusations call into question whether President Obama can fully rely on reports from the Central Administration on military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan and other hotspots.
Criticism of Islamic State intelligence is reminiscent of more than a decade ago, when Centcom's intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker released a study claiming that the George W. Bush administration started the Afghan war with too little thought about its possible consequences.
Hooker also played an important role in exposing the islamic state's intelligence issue.
Last year, officials reported that Hooker's team had discovered that, contrary to public reports, airstrikes on Islamic State oil plants had not significantly worsened the terrorist group's financial situation, as they had built temporary factories to sell oil on the black market.
The Times reported in the September issue that this discovery did not go beyond the walls of the Central Administration.
The commander of Centcom at the time, General Lloyd Austin III, received sharp criticism, as many lawmakers believed that war reports described the situation too positively.
In April, General Austin retired and was replaced by General Joseph L. Votel.
