The most depressing food of the depressive period is the "Hearty Meal"
In March 1933, shortly after his election as president, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down in the oval room for a meal.
President Roosevelt tasted fine culinary delicacies such as goose liver pate, or fuagra, and Maryland turtle soup.
But that day his meal was much more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and, for dessert, plum pudding.
Jane Ziegelman says, "It's a way to stand in solidarity in cooking with people who were doing very hard."
Her husband, Andrew Kou, adds, "It's also a message to Americans on how to eat."
A couple from the Brooklyn Heights district are food historians.
Kou's latest book, "Vegetable Stew," describes Chinese cuisine in America, while Ziegelman describes life through food in a rental home in lower Eastern Manhattan in her book "97 Apple Trees."
Their new joint work, "The Hearty Meal," which will be published Tuesday by the publishing house Harper, is a story about American food during the Great Depression.
Showing some solidarity in cooking, they had a meal with reporter Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a simple lunch eatery located in the Flatiron area and operating since 1929, when the Great Depression began.
The 54-year-old Mrs. Ziegelman ordered a sandwich with melted cheese and chopped olives, while 57-year-old Kou ordered turkey, mashed potatoes and vegetable salad.
When a reporter ordered the fake bunny, the couple admitted that his choice was very relevant to the conversation about the food of the time of the Great Depression .
Ms. Ziegelman said the fake bunny was very popular.
There was a peanut hare, a liver hare, and a bean hare.
They were made from the basic ingredient and other ingredients that enriched the meal.
Imagine what it's like to eat so many peanuts to be instead of lunch.
Mr. Kou groaned.
"It probably felt like my stomach was full of lead," he added.
In the pre-depressed years, the American dining table resembled a buffet, especially in rural areas.
The women prepared to eat for their husbands-laborers and freshly prepared casseroles were served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
During the First World War, it was the Americans who sent food to the Europeans. "The Hearty Meal" describes how Americans adapted to conditions when America suddenly ceased to be a land of abundance.
"At that time, food became the main object of attention of the American people in everyday life, "says Mr. Kou, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write specifically on this topic.
The new budget diets became just as important: unknown foods like fake bunny and stews became commonplace, stews were "a great way to take advantage of leftovers," Ms. Ziegelman noted, as cooks could hide the unattractive ingredients under a creamy sauce.
Fresh fruits were replaced by cheap dried fruits.
Meat, which for years was the main component of American meals, now became an extremely rare luxury item.
At a time when the number of calories and the nutritional value of food were more important than taste, new, unprecedented formations were born.
In an ancient cookbook, Mrs. Ziegelman found a recipe for making onions stuffed with peanut butter.
Mr. Kou adds, "It wasn't a popular addition to the dining table."
Ms. Ziegelman emphasizes, "It was surreal."
Peanut butter and fried onion are incompatible.
Many recipes of homemade dishes adapted to difficult times.
Household economists such as Louise Stanley, head of the Federal Bureau of Household Economics from 1923 to 1943, determined the country's eating habits that had not been experienced either before or after the Great Depression.
Publishing articles and recipes in newspapers and magazines, they advised housewives to become "economists" and accept such challenges as turning a mix of pasta and carrots into a delicious meal.
"Hearty Meal" is a feast of historical delicacies.
Evidence of the government's attitude toward its hungry citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's "let me eat a cake" attitude, is particularly interesting.
Although in public he talked about his simple childhood and catering in Iowa, in fact he ate like the fine millionaire he had become.
Mr Kou says, "He liked European cuisine like fish with cucumber sauce."
He ate in an almost gilded living room, wearing a lunch jacket.
He was completely disconnected from reality.
President Roosevelt would have made the same mistake unless his wife, Eleanor, had advised him to lead by example with his eating habits.
The book tells us that Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who didn't learn how to cook, so the White House became "a place where not only was one of the most tasteless dishes served in Washington, D.C., but also the worst-cooked dishes."
As soon as the country's economy recovered, most of the culinary customs of the Depression era disappeared.
But we continue to pay attention to calories and nutritional value, as well as how to apply science in cooking, Ms. Ziegelman added.
The couple say that while writing the book, they gained a greater understanding of Mrs. Ziegelman's mother's eating habits, such as why she couldn't throw food out.
"She was really afraid to throw food out," Mr. Kou said.
Ms. Ziegelman said, "She was actually freaking people out."
Once upon a time there was an incident with wind cakes.
After we had eaten at Eisenberg's eatery, a pair of writers pulled a homemade dessert out of their bag: plum pudding that President Roosevelt used to eat for lunch.
"It's plum whipped cream," Ms. Ziegelman said, adding that it was common at the time to give modest dishes a chic name.
There is no whipped cream in it, only prunes, a little flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
Everyone impatiently dipped the spoons in the brown mass that lay on the plates.
Surprisingly, it wasn't all that bad.
Mr. Kou ate a few more bites.
Sounding like an experienced "economist," he said to his wife, "A pinch of ground hazelnuts would do."
Gilead will receive a refund for legal expenses in the fight with Merck over the Hepatitis C patent
