Up to 2000 jobs, both direct and indirect, could be at risk.
In addition, it will also have unpredictable side effects, as the smelter consumes about 10 percent of victoria's entire power supply.
In 2014, Alcoa closed the "Point Henry" smelter, which led to a break in the operation of the Angleseas power plant.
Alkoas Portland's smelter is operating at a loss and may be closed.
These events were triggered by years of speculation about the rise in the value of the Australian dollar and the cost of the plant's production.
The plant's energy supplier, AGL, which supplies energy from its Loy Yang A power plant in the Latroube Valley, says it's likely the other three owners will also terminate their contracts.
Most of the power plant is owned by the joint venture "Alcoa" and "Alumia", in addition to the company's shares are owned by the holding companies of China "CITIC" and "Marubeni Corp" in Japan.
AGL is hoping for the continuation of the Portland plant, which would mean further energy supplies to the smelter," its spokesman said.
AGL said the contracts were so-called "risk-limiting contracts" that are expected to take effect from November 2016.
Contracts have a validity period of 12 months and will therefore remain in force until 2017.
AGL expects to receive revenue from these contracts for fiscal year 2017 as well," a company spokesperson said.
Starting from fiscal year 2018, the potential impact on profits is limited by favourable market forecasts for future wholesale electricity prices.
AGL claims to have already counted $187 million in losses in its forecasts — anticipating that those contracts would be terminated.
Alcoa says the decision to terminate the contracts will not affect Alcoa's ability to continue operating the smelter or supply it with energy.
The U.S. company says it signed a 20-year contract with Loy Yang in 2010, but it will be terminated in November. The Company does not provide any explanation as to why it will cease cooperation.
