The petition was created on August 10 and is currently signed by 55 people.
The process of nominating Inga Kolegova, an applicant for the position of Director General of the SRS, is opaque and unprofessional.
It brings to mind the best traditions of functionaries of the Soviet Union.
This discredits public administration and once again disappoints the public in government and politicians.
"There needs to be a contest with clear criteria against which all candidates must be judged," the petition's text reads.
Its author, John B., pointed out that the criteria for how Kolegov was chosen for the position are not known to the public.
It is also not clear what the candidate's intentions are for working for the SRS.
The petition states that the State Chancellery should create a new, open competition, in which professional candidates are actively addressed, personnel selection specialists are attracted and appropriate remuneration is offered.
Finance Minister Dana Reiznieces-Ozola officially nominated Kolegova for the post of head of the SRS last week, this week the government was supposed to confirm him to the new position, but all the ministers of the Unity party voted against, so the issue of a week was postponed.
