The turnover of the canning manufacturer "Blue Lagoon" fell by 33.8% last year.
The turnover of the canning manufacturer "Blue Lagoon" last year was 4.202 million euros, which is 33.8% less than a year earlier, while the company's losses decreased 5.7 times - to 904.7 thousand euros, according to the annual financial report published in the database "Lursoft".
The company's management report states that in 2015 the company worked with losses incurred for a number of reasons, including a constant shortage of working capital, which was caused by the departure of Unicredit Bank from the Baltic market, terminating the previously valid credit line, and leaving the "Blue Lagoon" with concluded contracts without the possibility of fulfilling them.
Consequently, the company did not have sufficient funds to purchase cheaper raw materials in large volumes and receive a volume discount.
The bank's departure from the Latvian market also prevented the company from implementing support projects from the European Union Structural Funds, which would have allowed the plant to purchase new production equipment and modernize the infrastructure.
Also, the company's financial indicators last year were negatively affected by the rise in raw material prices and the reluctance of customers to pay more for the goods produced by the company.
"Only in the second half of July 2016, customers recognized price changes and were ready to purchase goods at the new - the highest - prices", according to the company's management.
Also in 2015, "Blue Lagoon" began negotiations with potential investors, including the valuation of the company's movable and immovable property.
Investors have already been to the company's largest creditor, Unicredit Leasing, where the parties have become acquainted and discussed possible investment plans.
At the same time, the company's activities and development were positively affected by the implementation of the restructuring and optimization plan started in 2014 and 2015.
This plan included the improvement and optimization of technological processes, which allows to achieve greater production productivity and capacity.
"A number of equipment was purchased that provides a higher production speed," the company's management said.
The management of the "Blue Lagoon" notes that the purchased equipment in 2016 will allow the company's production facility to fulfill such orders that were not possible until now.
The first batch of production, which will be produced on this equipment, will be ready in August.
Since letters of intent on the sale of the product have already been signed, everything produced will be sold according to the letters of intent.
The new product will increase the turnover by about 300 thousand euros per month", according to the company's management.
In August 2016, the company also plans to sign a cooperation agreement on the supply of fish products to Iraq.
In 2016, the "Blue Lagoon" has sent the first experimental container to Israel, expanded the outlet to Cyprus and this September will sign a cooperation agreement with a new supermarket chain in the USA.
As a result of all the above measures, the company plans to increase turnover.
In 2014, "Blue Lagoon" worked with a turnover of 6.347 million euros and a loss of 5.113 million euros.
"Blue Lagoon" was founded in 1997 and its share capital is 1,156 million euros.
The company is owned by two Latvian individuals - Mikhail Kaidanov (89.11%) and Igor Shirshon (10.89%).
