Due to a neighbor's repair, a man is knocked to a shattered ceiling and forced to leave his home.
The ATV program "Studio 4" was approached by Dmitry Saidyashev, whose neighbor has begun overhaul in his apartment, and since then Dmitry has been crumbling plaster from the ceiling and is not sure that staying in the apartment is safe.
The problem is that my neighbors carried out arbitrary construction and the ceiling in my apartment is damaged.
Then I informed the Riga Construction Board, the building manager and other organizations.
The building board said we are not an operational service and we don't have any expertise.
"The owner of the apartment has to go to the Latvian Union of Engineers, and from there there will be an expert", says Dmitrijs.
The invited expert arrived, recorded what had happened and admitted that the covering was in unsatisfactory condition.
But a month has passed since Dmitry's first application to the construction board, and by the beginning of this week, no one could answer whether being in the apartment was not life-threatening.
The construction board said - this is the legislation, wait, if you are not satisfied, write to everyone in turn.
"Then I wrote to the Riga City Council, but they transferred the house to the manager, then the house manager again to the construction board, and then there is a dead end", says Dmitry.
After examining the entire pile of papers, what is clear is that the construction work has been suspended, although every now and then you can hear that someone is working there.
Within a further two months, an inspection had to be carried out and, within six months, all those defects had to be rectified by the owner of the apartment carrying out the repairs.
The independent expert has drawn up his opinion, but the construction board considers it incomplete and superficial.
The expert has not indicated whether the metal grid in this load-bearing structure has been affected, so there is no certainty that the owner of the lower apartment is in danger.
"Therefore, we have requested additional clarification from this expert," says Ilze Žūka, a representative of the Riga City Construction Board.
Despite the ban on carrying out any repair work in the upper apartment, from there it is still heard that construction continues.
The penalty for arbitrary construction without a building permit is from 70 to 700 euros, but in a particular case the penalty can be much more severe.
While awaiting the expert's opinion, the construction board has decided that both apartments should not be operated - both the one in which the construction work is taking place and Dmitry's apartment.
"This is an unprecedented case in the practice of the building board, where in this way, due to their ignorance or simply unwillingness, residents may have posed a threat not only to their property, but also to the owner of the lower property, as a result of which this owner cannot operate his property," says a spokeswoman for the construction board.
Now it remains for Dmitry to look for another place to live - with relatives, friends, in a hotel, or to rent another apartment.
But dmitry may try to recover the losses incurred from a neighbor in a civil manner, which, however, can take a lot of time.
Due to the arbitrary construction, it is currently forbidden to stay in both apartments until the civil engineer gives his conclusion, and it may have to wait up to three weeks.
The losses incurred will have to be covered by the owner of the apartment where the repairs took place.
The owner of this apartment, because he has not taken into account what the construction board said, also faces a prison sentence of up to six months.
