The president will present the Order of the Three Stars to the opera singer Antonenko.
President of Latvia Raimonds Vējonis will present the Order of the Three Stars' III class to opera singer Alexander Antonenko next week, August 16, according to the president's agenda.
The ceremony of awarding the Order of the Three Stars will be held at the House of Blackheads at 13 p.m.
According to the information provided by the Latvian National Opera and Ballet (LNOB), Antonenko graduated from Jāzeps Medinis College of Music in 1998, where he studied wind instruments and learned singing with Margarita Gruzdeva.
He studied at the Vocal Department of the Jāzeps Vītols Latvian Academy of Music in the class of Arvīds Luste.
In 1997 he started singing in the choir of the Latvian National Opera, but in 1998 he made his debut with the role of Oberto in G.F. Hendel's opera "Alčīna".
He received the "Great Music Award 2003" for his vocal performance in opera performances and Verdi's Requiem.
It is indicated that in the 2004/2005 season he became the most internationally recognized Latvian tenor, which is anglicised by the largest opera houses in the world.
Since autumn 2004, he has been singing "Düsseldorf's Deutsche Oper am Rhein", the Berlin and Graz Opera, the Dresden Semperoper, the Royal Opera in Oslo and Stockholm, the London Covent Garden Opera, the Monte Carlo Opera, the Vienna State Opera, as well as the Geneva, Dresden and Düsseldorf Opera and the Salzburg Festival.
Antonenko in 2009 with great success made his debut at the Metropolitan Opera in the role of the Prince in "The Mermaid".
In turn, in 2011, Antonenko sang the title role "Othello" at the Paris Opera with Ricardo Muti and the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, at the Covent Garden Opera he sang in the new production of Luigi "The Cloak", as well as in Stockholm he took part in the "Girl from the West" staged by Christoph Loy.
A year later, Antonenko sang with great success the role of Othello at London's Covent Garden Opera.
Former NATO commander Bradlow's email has been hacked by Russian hackers.
The hackers who hacked the computers of the U.S. Democratic National Committee (DNC) allegedly carried out several other cyberattacks also hacked the email of Philip Bradlow, a former commander of NATO's European forces, and the servers of the George Soros Institute's Open Society, business news agency Bloomberg reported Thursday.
Hackers have published the obtained information on the site "DCLeaks.com".
Among other things, Bridlow's correspondence and news of the work of the Soros Institute are also posted there.
For hackers, the institute's computers have been available for a whole year.
According to Bloomberg, these cyberattacks were carried out by the same hackers associated with Russian special services who hacked DNC emails.
The Wall Street Journal, for its part, reports that U.S. President Barack Obama's administration is currently considering imposing new sanctions on Russia in response to the hacking of DNC computers.
To implement sanctions, the administration will have to formally accuse Russia or hackers backed by Russian authorities in a cyberattack on Democratic Party servers.
The WikiLeaks website reportedly released about 20,000 emails in July obtained from the DNC's computer system, suggesting that Democratic Party leaders had tried to harm the campaign of party candidate Hillary Clinton's former rival, Vermont Senator Bernie Sanders, in the fight for a Democratic nomination to run in the presidential election.
As reported by U.S. press sources, the Federal Bureau of Investigation, which conducts an investigation into the hacking of Democratic servers, as well as other U.S. special services, believe Russia's connection to the cyberattack is almost unquestionable.
