NASA's climate model: Venus was once a habitable planet
Based on NASA's latest climate models, Venus has once been a habitable planet.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Research have developed a model to study the history of Venus using tools and algorithms that climate scientists also use.
The model was developed to determine whether there have ever been Earth-like conditions on Venus, whose surface is hot, where there is no water and whose atmosphere consists almost entirely of carbon.
Scientists have previously made guesses that the slow speed of rotation of Venus is explained by the dense atmosphere.
But recent simulations suggest that Venus once had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and was spinning slowly.
The model also looks at the earliest topography of Venus.
There were more arid areas on the planet than on Earth, but there was enough water and geographical diversity on it to allow life to form and prevent water from evaporating.
In the early days of Venus, the Sun was 30 percent brighter.
In the simulation of the GISS model, the Venus spin model reveals that the light part of the day on it lasts 2 months, GISS scientist Antony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This process heats the surface of the planet and causes rain, which, in turn, forms layers of thick clouds that act as an umbrella, protecting the planet from the heat of the Sun.
As a result, a moderate climate temperature is formed, which, in fact, is a few degrees lower than the temperature on Earth today.
The model depicts the history of Venus, which is similar to the theory of evolution developed by scientists in their hypotheses.
Although it was once habitable, over the billions of years Venus has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet rays.
Its oceans evaporated, and the spirits were burned out by ultraviolet rays.
As the water evaporated completely, only a thin atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse gas remained - Venus as we know it today.
The scientists published the results of the new climate model of Venus in the journal "Geophysical Research Letters".
Patrick Roy resigns as Avalanche coach
On Thursday, Colorado Avalanche coach and vice president of hockey operations Patrick Roy submitted his resignation, citing as a reason the insufficient influence in the team's decision-making process.
Colorado vice president and general manager Joe Sakik confirmed the news and informed that the club would immediately begin looking for a new coach.
"For the past three years, I have performed my duties energetically, passionately and purposefully as head coach and vice president of hockey operations at the Colorado club," the 50-year-old Roy said in a statement.
Over the course of this summer, I've been thinking a lot about how I could improve the team's performance to give it the brilliance it needs and achieve higher-level results.
To achieve this, the visions of the head coach and vice president of hockey operations must fully coincide with those of the organization.
He should also be able to influence decisions that relate to the performance of the team.
At the moment, these conditions are not met.
Sakik, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his contributions to the team.
Sakik said Patrick informed him of his decision today.
We appreciate everything he has done for the organization and wish him all the best in the future.
In his first season with the Avalanche team in 2013-2014, Roy was recognized as the league's best coach and received the Jack Adams Award.
He helped the club reach 112 points and first place in the Central Division, but in the first round of the playoffs, the Colorado team was defeated by Minnesota hockey players. Since then, the club has not made it to the playoffs for two years.
The Avalanche finished the 2015-2016 season with a score of 39-39-4 and remained five points behind the Wild team without winning the Western Conference hosts' second special invitation.
Hall of Fame goaltender Roy won four Stanley Cups in his career — two with the Montreal Canadiens and two with the Avalanche.
North Sea oil rig workers resume talks and postpone strike
Workers' strikes on North Sea oil rig workers' pay have been postponed as the two sides in the dispute have resumed talks, according to negotiators.
Periodically, strikes are held against the oil processing company "Wood Group" on the oil platforms of the North Sea, in which the company "Royal Dutch Shell" operates.
The joint statement said the Wood Group and United and RMT unions had agreed to resume talks to resolve the dispute.
Several full-day meetings are scheduled for the coming weeks, which will begin early next week with the aim of revisiting the issues at stake.
The unions said their recent events, organized after more than 25 years of hiatus, targeted a planned 30 percent pay cut.
Due to negative market pressures, Wood Group cut wages for North Sea workers by 9 percent this year.
Already in 2014, the company reduced the wages of land workers by 10 percent.
The company explains that additional salary cuts would allow the company to survive the market downturn.
Shell, meanwhile, has already cut salaries for several thousand people and announced plans to shut down oil and natural gas operations in 10 countries to optimise its work in preparation for a large-scale merger deal with British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure because of falling oil prices, and the situation is further complicated by Britain's decision to leave the European Union.
Earlier in the week, Scottish MP Dave Anderson met with workers' representatives to discuss one of the most important issues, the North Sea strike plans.
He said the North Sea is vital to the region's economy.
In his report, he explains that the North Sea and the country as a whole need an economy that benefits everyone, not individuals.
In 2016, nearly $1.4 billion is expected to be invested in new North Sea projects, up from $7 billion invested over the past five years.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the constellation Pleiades.
The mission of the latest Kepler telescope has helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of the speed of rotation of stars in the constellation Pleiades.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in this constellation rotate at different speeds, as well as how the speed of rotation of stars refers to the formation of planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other constellations, we will get more information about the relationship between star mass, age, and even the history of its solar system," Luisa Rebula, a scientist at Pasadenas Caltech's Infrared Processes and Analytical Center, told a news release.
The constellation Pleiades is located at a distance of 445 light years from Earth.
Many stars in this constellation are just beginning to rise, reaching the age of about 125 million years.
They rotate at maximum speed.
Rotating at maximum speed, these rising stars emit a large amount of stellar wind.
As the winds enter the magnetic field of the stars, they brake the stars.
As the stars age, their speed of rotation decreases.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star, determining the time between the appearance of recognizable areas of stars, such as solar spots.
The latest catalog of the speed of rotation of stars shows that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller stars.
Rebul compares stars with dancers, dancers of greater stature perform pirouettes more slowly than dancers of small stature.
Rebul says the Pleiades' "ballet" shows that slow-rotating objects are larger and more massive, while faster-rotating objects are very small stars.
Thanks to the fact that the constellation Pleiades is located so close, it serves as an excellent space laboratory, where you can compare the characteristics of stars with the speeds of rotation.
Rebul tells us that the constellation Pleiades helps to create theoretical models for the rotation of stars in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have a lot to learn how, when and why the speed of rotation of stars slows down and about their complete stop process.
Rebul and his colleagues presented in detail an analysis of the speeds of rotation of the Pleiades stars in three new publications, which will soon be published in the Journal of Astronomy.
